article.headline: South Florida 59, Rutgers 56
article.story:
PISCATAWAY, N.J. -- Shantia Grace did more than give South Florida one of its biggest wins in women's basketball with a late three-point play.

The senior also put some doubt in the mind of Rutgers coach C. Vivian Stringer whether the once highly thought of Scarlet Knights can make the NCAA tournament this season.

Grace snapped a tie with her three-point play with 7.9 seconds to play and South Florida beat Rutgers 59-56 after blowing a 19-point second-half lead on Saturday.

"This is a big win," Grace said. "I've been here four years and we haven't won (against them). It was a close game my freshman year and it came down to missed free throw with me. But this is Rutgers, a team that's always in the Top 25 so this is a big win."

The Bulls (16-6, 3-5 Big East Conference) had to sweat out both the final minutes and seconds.

The Scarlet Knights (12-7, 4-4) tied the game with a late 17-0 run, and they had another chance to force overtime in the waning seconds. Epiphanny Prince's running 25-footer, however, banked off the backboard and rolled off the rim.

Stringer was at a loss to explain how Rutgers knocked off No. 17 Notre Dame on the road earlier in the week for their first win over a ranked team this season and then failed to show up for a 19-minute stretch where her team was outscored 28-4 by South Florida.

"I don't know what to expect," she said. "I wish I did."

Her concern now is the NCAA tournament. Rutgers played in the title game two years ago and was within a game of making it back to the Final Four last year before Connecticut rallied to end their season.

With roughly a month left in the season, Stringer is concerned looking at the schedule. The Scarlet Knights will play at No.1 Connecticut on Tuesday, the first of two games left with the Huskies. They also have games against No. 8 Maryland and No. 21 Pittsburgh along with one against Georgetown, which crushed South Florida recently.

"I am greatly concerned," Stringer said of her team's NCAA chances. "I don't think this record is good enough to get us into the NCAAs, and that's the truth. And you know what? We just have to deal with it."

A point of note. Rutgers made the NCAA tournament in 2003-04 with 11 losses.

Janae Stokes added 20 points as South Florida beat Rutgers for the first time in four meetings.

The Bulls seemingly took total control with a 28-4 spurt bridging the halves and then fell apart in the final five-plus minutes as they turned the ball over six times, allowing Rutgers to run off 17 straight points.

"We knew they weren't going to go away," coach Jose Fernandez said. "Every coach in this league says how good this league is from top to bottom. We now have a day to prepare for Marquette, but this is a big win for our kids."

Brittany Ray tied the game with a 3-pointer with just under a minute to go.

Grace then missed the front end of a one-and-one with 47 seconds to play, giving Rutgers a chance to take the lead.

However, the Scarlet Knights could not get off a shot and turned the ball over on a shot clock violation with under 16 seconds to play.

Grace broke the Rutgers' press -- which had been so lethal in the comeback -- and drove the lane for an off-balance layup, giving the Bulls their final lead and their first win over Rutgers in four tries.

"Coach told us before the game that they are hard to score on five on five, so any fastbreak opportunity, we should take it," said Grace, who finished with nine points on 2 of 8 shooting. "I knew the clock was running down and it was an open area, so I just took it. It was actually kind of a lucky shot. I just wanted to drive hard to the basket and throw it up and give it a chance to go in."

It did.

Prince had 25 points to lead Rutgers, including 10 in the 17-0 run. Ray added 12 for the Scarlet Knights, who shot just under 33 percent for the game.

"This raises the urgency for us to finish out the entire season," Ray said. "We didn't have to lose to USF. I think if played the beginning like we did the last eight minutes I think we would have been fine."
